proof.p:
Before we start doing the algebra, let us recall that (X+Y)^2=X^2+2XY+Y^2. We will need this formula from to . Now we manipulate the quadratic function from the general form into the vertex form.
f(x) \amp = ax^2+bx+c f(x) \amp = ax^2+bx+\frac{b^2}{4a} - \frac{b^2}{4a}+c f(x) \amp = a(x^2+\frac{b}{a}x+\frac{b^2}{4a^2}) - \frac{b^2}{4a}+c f(x) \amp = a(x^2+2\frac{b}{2a}x + (\frac{b}{2a})^2) - \frac{b^2}{4a}+c f(x) \amp = a(x+\frac{b}{2a})^2-\frac{b^2}{4a}+c f(x) \amp = a(x+\frac{b}{2a})^2-\frac{b^2-4ac}{4a}
By renaming h = -\frac{b}{2a}, k = -\frac{b^2-4ac}{4a}, we have f(x)=a(x-h)^2+k

Take Equation , if we want to solve the quadratic equation  ax^2+bx+c = 0, it is enough to solve the equation  a(x+\frac{b}{2a})^2-\frac{b^2-4ac}{4a} = 0 This is easy to solve because we have

					a(x+\frac{b}{2a})^2-\frac{b^2-4ac}{4a} \amp = 0
					a(x+\frac{b}{2a})^2 \amp = \frac{b^2-4ac}{4a}
					(x+\frac{b}{2a})^2 \amp = \frac{b^2-4ac}{4a^2}
					x+\frac{b}{2a} \amp = \pm \sqrt{\frac{b^2-4ac}{4a^2}}
					x \amp = -\frac{b}{2a} \pm \sqrt{\frac{b^2-4ac}{4a^2}} 
					x \amp = \frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}

				Equation  is the well-known quadratic formula that you have seen before.

